OAuth and OIDC in Simple TermsFirst, what is OAuth?

ğŸ‘‰ OAuth (Open Authorization) is a way to let users log in to your app using another service (like Google, Facebook, GitHub) without sharing their password.

Itâ€™s mainly used for authorization â€” which means deciding what the user is allowed to do.

Example:

You open a website and click â€œLogin with Google.â€

Your app redirects you to Googleâ€™s login page.

You log in to Google (so you never share your Google password with that app).

Google sends your app an access token â€” like a permission slip.

Your app uses that token to access your basic Google data (like your email).

âœ… So, OAuth helps your app get permission to use another appâ€™s data safely.

OIDC (OpenID Connect)
what about OIDC (OpenID Connect)?

ğŸ‘‰ OIDC is built on top of OAuth.
OAuth only tells what the user can do (authorization),
but OIDC also tells who the user is (authentication).

So, OIDC gives you user identity (like name, email, profile info) along with the access token.
